The HD 219666 Exoplanetary System


Overview

HD 219666 is a star with 0.92 times the mass of the Sun, and 1.03 times its radius. It is located 307.15 light years away from the solar system and is estimated to be 10 billion years old, as compared to the Sun which is roughly 4.6 billion years old.

HD 219666 is known to have 1 exoplanets in orbit around it.


Exoplanets in the HD 219666 system


HD 219666 b

HD 219666 b was discovered by the Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite (TESS) observatory, in 2019-03, using the transit method. Its semi-major axis is 0.06 astronomical units, as compared to Earth's which is 1 astronomical unit. The mass of HD 219666 b is 16.609 times the mass of Earth. The radius of HD 219666 b is 4.710 that of Earth. At more than 10 Earth masses, HD 219666 b is an ice giant, a planet that is made up mostly of volatiles like water, amonia and methane, and enveloped by a dense hydrogen and helium atmosphere, much like Uranus and Neptune in our solar system.
